## Part B — Karpenter (node autoscaling)

### What Karpenter is

- **Karpenter** is a **node provisioning** controller: it watches **unschedulable pods** and **creates/removes nodes** (on AWS: EC2 instances) to fit workload shape — fast **bin-packing**, **consolidation**, and **right-sized** instance types.
- It is **not** a replacement for **Cluster Autoscaler (CA)** in the sense of “pick one for everything” — on many AWS EKS setups you run **Karpenter instead of CA** for worker scaling, or use **one** node-autoscaling solution to avoid fighting.

### Karpenter vs Cluster Autoscaler — tradeoffs

| Topic | **Cluster Autoscaler (CA)** | **Karpenter** |
|-------|----------------------------|---------------|
| **Model** | Scales **existing Auto Scaling Groups** (add/remove nodes in fixed **instance-type pools**). | **Directly provisions** instances per **NodePool** constraints (AWS: **EC2NodeClass** + **NodePool** in v1 API). |
| **Speed** | Waits for ASG cooldowns; **slower** scale-out when pools are wrong-sized. | Often **faster** to place pending pods — creates nodes that **match pod requests** (CPU/mem/gpu/arch). |
| **Flexibility** | Limited to **predefined** ASG instance types / sizes. | **Broader** instance diversification under constraints — better **utilization** if policies allow. |
| **Cost / ops** | Predictable if ASGs are simple; **underutilized** nodes if pools are coarse. | **Consolidation** can **evict** and **replace** nodes to save cost — **more aggressive**; needs **PodDisruptionBudgets** and app tolerance to rescheduling. |
| **Complexity** | Fewer moving parts if you already live in ASG-only world. | **IAM**, **Subnet / SG** wiring, **NodePool** YAML, **interruption** handling (spot) — steeper **initial** platform design. |
| **Multi-AZ** | ASG per AZ pattern is well understood. | Must design **NodePools** + **topology** so spread and **capacity** stay balanced. |

**One-liner for interviews:** *“CA scales **fixed node groups**; Karpenter **provisions nodes from constraints** — faster and more flexible, but you must design for **consolidation**, **interruptions**, and **IAM** correctly.”*

### Install outline (AWS EKS — typical)

> Exact API names shifted in **Karpenter v1** (`NodePool`, `EC2NodeClass`). Align commands with the **version** you deploy.

1. **IAM** — Karpenter needs permissions to **create instances**, **pass InstanceProfile**, **describe** EC2/Subnets/SGs, **tag**, and integrate with **EKS** (use official **Terraform** or **Helm + IRSA** docs for your version).
2. **Subnet / SG** — **tags** on subnets (discovery), **security groups** that allow **node ↔ control plane** and **workload** traffic.
3. **Helm install** — `karpenter` chart into `karpenter` namespace; **service account** with **IRSA**.
4. **Define `EC2NodeClass` + `NodePool`** (v1) — instance families, **limits**, **taints**, **startup taints**, **consolidation** policy.
5. **(Optional)** **Interruption queue** — SQS + **interruption handling** for spot / rebalance (version-specific).

### How to check it is working

1. **Pods pending** — deploy a Deployment that **requests** more CPU/mem than current nodes can satisfy (or use a **toleration** only a new NodePool satisfies).
2. **Watch** — `kubectl get nodes -w` and Karpenter logs:
   ```bash
   kubectl -n karpenter logs -l app.kubernetes.io/name=karpenter -f
   ```
3. **Expect** — new **Node** appears, pod **Scheduled**, Karpenter events show **provisioning** / **launched**.
4. **Scale down** — delete workload or let **consolidation** run (if enabled); nodes **drain** / **terminate** per policy (respect **PDBs**).

```bash
kubectl get nodepools          # or NodePool depending on API version
kubectl get ec2nodeclasses     # or EC2NodeClass
kubectl describe nodepool <name>
```

### Platform pitfalls

- **Bin-packing vs PDB:** aggressive consolidation **evicts** pods — apps need **graceful shutdown** and **PDBs**.
- **Spot + databases:** usually a **bad default** unless you know **interruption** handling.
- **Single controller:** do **not** run **CA and Karpenter** both trying to own the same **worker** capacity without a **clear** split (e.g. separate node groups) — causes **thrash**.

